instances.text: SPAN_V 321-101 - Tradition and Diversity in Spanish History and Culture

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
Title: Tradition and Diversity in Spanish History and Culture | A panoramic view of the history and culture of Spain from prehistoric times to the end of the 17th century. Understand how Spain's plural identity has been in a constant struggle between centre and periphery, and between tradition and progress.  
See the full course overview: https://fhis.ubc.ca/course-description/SPAN321  

Contact us here: https://fhis.ubc.ca/undergraduate-advising-contact-form/ 

Language of instruction: Spanish

instances.text: SPAN_V 357-101 - The Golden Age of Peninsular Literature and Culture

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
What makes great fiction? Discover Medieval and Golden Age literature, through renowned masterpieces of storytelling that have shaped Spain, Latin America and cultures across the world. 
This is one of the required courses for Minor and Major in Spanish 

See the full course overview: https://fhis.ubc.ca/course-description/SPAN357  

Contact us here: https://fhis.ubc.ca/undergraduate-advising-contact-form/ 

Language of instruction: Spanish

instances.text: SPAN_V 364-101 - Colonial Encounters in Spanish-American Lit and Culture

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
What is colonialism, and what is its legacy in Latin America? In this course, we will aim to answer this question through the analysis of several canonical texts of the so-called “colonial literature” while considering a wide variety of perspectives (indigenous, mestizo, Spanish, Creole, etc.) and reflecting on decolonial pedagogy. 
This is one of the required courses for Minor and Major in Spanish 

See the full course overview: https://fhis.ubc.ca/course-description/SPAN364/  

Contact us here: https://fhis.ubc.ca/undergraduate-advising-contact-form/

detailResultFields.label: Course Section Definition Public Notes
detailResultFields.value:
Course Description: The conditions in which we live and work can affect our health. Key concepts of social determinants of population health include: poverty, economic resources, education, policy, neighbourhood conditions, early child development, and access to housing.

Open to all students. 

Registration Note: SPPH does not facilitate registration in this class, does not manually maintain a wait list, and will not force register additional students once the class limit has been reached. If the class is full, please monitor enrolment numbers and add yourself to the waitlist. You may also wish to check enrolment numbers one or two weeks before the course start date as there may be some movement at that time.
